            <p>
                There are seven classes of Strong Verb, each with a specific signature root and conjugation pattern.
                So Class II verbs always have an (eo + consonant) in the root. For example, '<em>beowan - to chew</em>'
                or
                '<em>fleogan - to fly</em>'. While Class VI verbs can have an (a + consonant or e/ie + double consnant).
                For example, '<em>wascan - to wash</em>' or '<em>sceððan - to injure</em>'.
            </p>
