            <h3>Rules to remember</h3>
            <p><strong>I-mutation</strong> occurs in most Strong Verbs in the 2nd and 3rd person singular present. So
                '<em>Ic cweþe - I say</em>' becomes '<em>Þu cwist - you say</em>' and '<em>heo cwiþ - she says</em>'. Do
                not get confused between the root vowel change when a verb moves to the past tense, '<em>heo cwæþ - she
                    said</em>'
                and i-mutation in the present.
            </p>
            <p><strong>Verners law</strong> causes <abbr title="a consonant made with no audible sound in the
                throat">voiceless stops</abbr> to change to a <abbr
                    title="a consonant made with a sound in the throat">voiced stop</abbr>
                if it is not the first or final letter, next to other voiceless consonants, or not immediately
                proceeded by the stress. This means that when verbs with letters like '<strong>þ</strong>' directly
                after the vowel
                conjugate, the '<strong>þ</strong>' changes to a <strong>d</strong> and <strong>s</strong> changes
                <strong>r</strong>.
            </p>
            <p><strong>Double consonants</strong> 
                If a difficult to pronounce double consonant would be produced by conjugation, it will be simplified
                so that it is easier to pronounce. So if
                a '<strong>þ/ð</strong>' comes after an unvoiced consonant like '<strong>t</strong>', it
                becomes a '<strong>t</strong>' also. 
                So '<em>hatan</em>' conjugates to '<em>heo hætt - she orders</em>' not
                '<em>heo hætþ</em>'. Similiarly, if a '<strong>þ</strong>' comes after a
                '<strong>d</strong>',
                they become '<strong>tt</strong>'. For example, '<em>rædan</em>' becomes '<em>heo rætt -
                she advises</em>', not '<em>heo rætþ</em>'.
            </p>
